<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="9" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="10.[192,527,1050,1107]" box="[192,338,1083,1107]" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">
(
<figureCitation box="[201,330,1083,1107]" captionStart="Figures 29–33" captionStartId="23.[192,287,1452,1474]" captionTargetBox="[192,1440,213,1421]" captionTargetId="figure-55@23.[192,1440,213,1421]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="Figures 29–33. Phoebella spp. 29–30) Phoebella phoebe, dorsal habitus. 29) Male. 30) Female. 31–32) Phoebe tinga, holotype male. 31) Dorsal habitus. 32) Lateral habitus. 33) Phoebella phoebe, male, antennomeres XI–XII." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5458932" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5458932/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Fig. 29–33</figureCitation>
)
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[190,1442,1131,1647]" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,394,1131,1155]" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Redescription.</emphasis>
Head not wider than prothorax; frons with projections in male, with or without transverse carina between projections; frons in female without projections. Antennal tubercles distant from each other. Eyes not divided; area of connection of eye lobes narrow (with 2–3 rows of ommatidia) or very narrow (with one row of ommatidia); distance between upper eye lobes variable. Antennae 12-segmented, distinctly longer than body length in both sexes, especially in male; scape without basal curvature, without apical cicatrix, shorter than antennomere III; pedicel much shorter than antennomere III and scape; antennomeres cylindrical, with long, sparse, erect setae ventrally on III–V or III–VI; antennomere III not tumid, without denser long setae; antennomere IV shorter than III; antennomere XII not stingershaped. Prothorax slightly longer than wide, or slightly wider than long; about as wide anteriorly as posteriorly, or slightly wider posteriorly; sides sinuous, without tubercle. Elytra narrowed from base to apex; humeral carina well-marked from base to near apex; area between humeral carina and epipleural margin without carinae, without whitish pubescence contrasting with that on dorsal surface, gradually more distinctly visible in dorsal view from posterior after middle; dorsal surface without longitudinal carinae; apex individually rounded, without projections at outer and sutural angles or slightly obliquely truncate; sutural area without long and erect setae. Metatarsomere I tumid or not; tarsal claws not divided basally, with inner tooth moderately shorter than outer one.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="10" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="10.[190,1440,1672,1926]" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,323,1672,1696]" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lane" authorityYear="1966" box="[330,448,1672,1696]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Phoebella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[330,448,1672,1696]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Phoebella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is very similar to 
<emphasis box="[666,759,1672,1696]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Audinet-Serville" authorityYear="1835" box="[666,754,1672,1696]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Lauraceae" genus="Phoebe" kingdom="Plantae" order="Laurales" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Phoebe</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
differing only by the antennae distinctly 12-segmented, while in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Audinet-Serville" authorityYear="1835" box="[299,385,1705,1729]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Lauraceae" genus="Phoebe" kingdom="Plantae" order="Laurales" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[299,385,1705,1729]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Phoebe</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
they are 11-segmented. It is also similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Lepeletier and Audinet-Serville, 1825" authorityName="Lepeletier and Audinet-Serville" authorityYear="1825" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Adesmus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[927,1037,1705,1729]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Adesmus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Lepeletier De Saint Fargeau, A. L. M. &amp; J. G. Audinet-Serville" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" refId="ref14630" refString="Lepeletier De Saint Fargeau, A. L. M., and J. G. Audinet-Serville. 1825. p. 335. In: M. Latreille. Encyclopedie methodique. Histoire naturelle. Entomologie, ou histoire naturelle des Crustaces, des Arachnides et des insectes. Vol. 10 (1). Mme veuve Agasse; Paris. 344 p." type="book" year="1825">Lepeletier and Audinet-Serville, 1825</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, differing by the antennae 12-segmented (11-segmented in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lepeletier and Audinet-Serville" authorityYear="1825" box="[963,1073,1738,1762]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Adesmus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[963,1073,1738,1762]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Adesmus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and by the frons in male with distinct projections (absent in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lepeletier and Audinet-Serville" authorityYear="1825" box="[558,668,1771,1795]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Adesmus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[558,668,1771,1795]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Adesmus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). According to 
<bibRefCitation author="Martins, U. R. &amp; M. H. M. Galileo" box="[850,1193,1771,1795]" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" pagination="5 - 231" refId="ref15067" refString="Martins, U. R., and M. H. M. Galileo, 2014 a. Subfamilia Lamiinae. Tribo Hemilophini. Parte I, p. 5 - 231. In: U. R. Martins (org.). Cerambycidae Sul-Americanos (Coleoptera). Taxonomia. V. 13. Sociedade Brasileira de Entomologia; Curitiba. 231 p." type="book chapter" year="2014">Martins and Galileo (2014a)</bibRefCitation>
(translated): “Frons in male with curved spine on each side of a curved elevation between the spines.” Actually, this curved carina between the projections of frons is present or absent depending on the particular species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Audinet-Serville" authorityYear="1835" box="[1353,1438,1836,1860]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Lauraceae" genus="Phoebe" kingdom="Plantae" order="Laurales" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1353,1438,1836,1860]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Phoebe</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and the projections may or may not be placed near antennal tubercles (e.g. 
<figureCitation box="[1126,1213,1869,1893]" captionStart="Figures 17–28" captionStartId="22.[192,287,1826,1848]" captionTargetBox="[193,1439,214,1794]" captionTargetId="figure-93@22.[192,1440,213,1794]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="Figures 17–28. Males. 17–18) Phoebe alba. 17) Eye and gena. 18) Metatarsus. 19) Phoebe cava, eye and gena. 20) Phoebe mafra, holotype, eye and gena. 21–22) Phoebe cornuta. 21) Eye and gena. 22) Metatarsus. 23–24) Phoebe goiana, holotype. 23) Eye and gena. 24) Metatarsus. 25–26) Phoebe bicornis. 25) Eye and gena. 26) Metatarsus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5458930" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5458930/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Fig. 21</figureCitation>
). Accordingly, this feature is useless to separate 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lane" authorityYear="1966" box="[554,672,1902,1926]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Phoebella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[554,672,1902,1926]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Phoebella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Audinet-Serville" authorityYear="1835" box="[745,831,1902,1926]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Lauraceae" genus="Phoebe" kingdom="Plantae" order="Laurales" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[745,831,1902,1926]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Phoebe</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[191,1440,215,271]" pageId="11" pageNumber="10">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,430,215,239]" pageId="11" pageNumber="10">Species included.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="(Gahan, 1889)" baseAuthorityName="Gahan" baseAuthorityYear="1889" box="[435,908,215,239]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Phoebella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albomaculata">
<emphasis box="[435,726,215,239]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="10">Phoebella albomaculata</emphasis>
(Gahan, 1889)
</taxonomicName>
; 
<taxonomicName authority="(Lepeletier and Audinet-Serville, 1825)" baseAuthorityName="Lepeletier and Audinet-Serville" baseAuthorityYear="1825" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Saperda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="phoebe">
<emphasis box="[918,1032,215,239]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="10">P. phoebe</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Lepeletier De Saint Fargeau, A. L. M. &amp; J. G. Audinet-Serville" pageId="11" pageNumber="10" refId="ref14630" refString="Lepeletier De Saint Fargeau, A. L. M., and J. G. Audinet-Serville. 1825. p. 335. In: M. Latreille. Encyclopedie methodique. Histoire naturelle. Entomologie, ou histoire naturelle des Crustaces, des Arachnides et des insectes. Vol. 10 (1). Mme veuve Agasse; Paris. 344 p." type="book" year="1825">Lepeletier and Audinet-Serville, 1825</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
; 
<taxonomicName authority="(Martins and Galileo, 1998)" baseAuthorityName="Martins and Galileo" baseAuthorityYear="1998" box="[274,720,247,271]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Phoebella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tinga">
<emphasis box="[274,371,248,271]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="10">P. tinga</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Martins, U. R. &amp; M. H. M. Galileo" box="[386,711,247,271]" pageId="11" pageNumber="10" pagination="431 - 437" refId="ref15019" refString="Martins, U. R., and M. H. M. Galileo. 1998. Generos de Hemilophini (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae) semelhantes a Phoebe Audinet-Serville, 1835. Revista Brasileira de Entomologia 41 (2 - 4): 431 - 437." type="journal article" year="1998">Martins and Galileo, 1998</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
